      "parameters": {
        "jsCode": "// Build OpenAI request payload while preserving original email data\nconst email = $input.item.json;\nconst senderEmail = email.from?.emailAddress?.address || '';\nconst senderDomain = senderEmail.split('@')[1] || '';\n\n// Check if sender is from company domain\nconst isInternalEmployee = senderDomain === 'surterreproperties.com';\n\nconst payload = {\n  model: \"gpt-3.5-turbo\",\n  messages: [\n    {\n      role: \"system\",\n      content: \"You are a classifier for IT helpdesk emails. Classify emails as:\\n\\n- 'support': Real technical issues, problems, or help requests from EMPLOYEES (printers, login issues, Wi-Fi, software problems, hardware issues, access requests, VPN issues, application errors, etc.)\\n\\n- 'vendor': ALL of the following:\\n  * Marketing emails, promotional content, newsletters\\n  * Automated/transactional emails from EXTERNAL services (verification codes, password resets from DigitalOcean/AWS/etc., receipts, confirmations)\\n  * Invoices, billing notifications\\n  * Social media notifications\\n  * Third-party service emails (DigitalOcean, AWS, Stripe, Mailchimp, etc.)\\n  * No-reply emails (noreply@, do-not-reply@)\\n\\n- 'unclear': Only if completely ambiguous\\n\\nKEY RULES:\\n1. Check sender domain: @surterreproperties.com = EMPLOYEE (likely support)\\n2. If employee asking for password reset/help → 'support'\\n3. If automated email from external service → 'vendor'\\n4. Employee requests ALWAYS take priority\\n5. Look for help-seeking language: \\\"I need\\\", \\\"Can you\\\", \\\"Please help\\\", \\\"How do I\\\" → 'support'\\n6. Automated language: \\\"Click here\\\", \\\"Verify your\\\", \\\"Your code is\\\" → 'vendor'\\n\\nReturn ONLY valid JSON: {\\\"class\\\":\\\"support|vendor|unclear\\\",\\\"confidence\\\":0.0-1.0,\\\"reason\\\":\\\"brief text\\\",\\\"priority\\\":\\\"low|normal|high\\\"}\"\n    },\n    {\n      role: \"user\",\n      content: `From: ${senderEmail}${isInternalEmployee ? ' (INTERNAL EMPLOYEE)' : ' (EXTERNAL)'}\\nSubject: ${email.subject}\\nBody: ${email.bodyPreview}`\n    }\n  ],\n  temperature: 0.1,\n  response_format: { type: \"json_object\" },\n  // Preserve original email data for later nodes\n  _originalEmail: email\n};\n\nreturn { json: payload };"
      },
